<br>
You can set the voice commands to whatever keyboard function you want.  For instance we use &quot;target one&quot; to activate the F2 key, which is the first person on the group list.  Or one we use a lot for our Shaman is &quot;assist&quot; which activates the &quot;assist &lt;main tank's name&gt;&quot; hotkey, then &quot;slow&quot; which activates the &quot;cast 2&quot; hotkey casting whatever slow spell we're using.<br>
<br>
The other nice thing about GameVoice is if you can put some friends together who have them.  Makes hunting together unbelievably easy, no more typing to communicate with each other.  You can have a live channel open to 5 other people while playing EQ.  The little console has buttons on it to active all the channels at once or each channel individually and a button to switch from using voice commands to live chat.  <br>
<br>
We ran into a guild on another server that required Gamevoice to join.  It made their guild hunts smooth and efficient as well as a lot of fun.<br>
<br>
We bought ours quite a while ago when they first came out for around $80 each.  The last time I checked, Best Buy had them for around $25.  I apologize for this getting so long, but it really is a nice voice recognition/live communication device for the money.<br>
